exports[`Admonitions — @info, @note, @deprecated > orderBy (multiple @info) 1`] = `
"# orderBy()

> **orderBy**\\<\`T\`\\>(\`array\`, \`iteratees\`, \`orders?\`): \`T\`[]

Sorts an array by multiple criteria with configurable sort orders.

:::info[WHY WRAPPING NATIVE?]

We prefer to wrap this method to ensure **Immutability** instead of the native \`sort\` which mutates. See [Design Philosophy](/guide/contribution/design-principles/design-philosophy/)

:::

:::info[WHY DUAL ITERATEE SIGNATURE?]

Unlike other Arkhe functions that use function-only iteratees,
\`orderBy\` accepts both \`keyof T\` and functions. This exception exists because multi-criteria sorting
(often 3+ fields) benefits significantly from the ergonomic \`['age', 'score', 'name']\` syntax over
the verbose \`[u => u.age, u => u.score, u => u.name]\`. The runtime cost of \`typeof\` checks is O(k)
where k is the number of criteria (typically 1-3), negligible compared to the O(n log n) sort.

:::

:::note[STABLE SORT]

elements with equal values maintain their relative order.

:::


---

## Type Parameters

### T: \`T\`

The type of elements in the array.

---

## Parameters

### array: \`readonly T[]\`

The array to sort.

### iteratees: \`(keyof T | (item) => unknown)[]\`

Property keys or functions to extract sort values.

### orders?: <TypeRef>[SortOrder](#sortorder)[]</TypeRef>

Sort orders for each iteratee. Defaults to \`'asc'\` for all.

---

## Returns: \`T[]\`

A new sorted array.

---

## Since

2.0.0

---

## Performance

O(n log n) time, O(n) space. Pre-computes criteria to avoid repeated function calls during sort.

---

## Also known as

<AlsoKnownAs data={{"lodash":{"name":"orderBy","group":"Collection"},"ramda":{"name":"sortWith","group":"List"},"radashi":{"name":"sort","group":"Array"},"remeda":{"name":"sortBy","group":"Array"},"moderndash":{"name":"sort","group":"Array"},"antfu":null,"effect":{"name":"sortWith","group":"Array"},"es-toolkit":{"name":"orderBy","group":"array"},"python":{"name":"sorted","group":"builtins"},"kotlin":{"name":"sortedWith","group":"collections"}}} />


---

## Example

\`\`\`typescript
const users = [
  { name: 'John', age: 25, score: 85 },
  { name: 'Bob', age: 25, score: 80 },
  { name: 'Jane', age: 30, score: 90 }
];

// Using property keys (ergonomic)
orderBy(users, ['age', 'score'], ['asc', 'desc']);
// => [{ name: 'John', age: 25, score: 85 }, { name: 'Bob', age: 25, score: 80 }, { name: 'Jane', age: 30, score: 90 }]

// Using functions (for computed values)
orderBy(users, [u => u.age, u => u.name.length], ['asc', 'desc']);
\`\`\`

---

## How it works?

Sorts by multiple criteria with configurable sort orders (asc/desc).
Unlike native \`sort()\`, returns a new array (immutable).
<ResponsiveMermaid
  desktop={\`flowchart LR
    A["[{age:25,score:85},
      {age:25,score:80},
      {age:30,score:90}]"]
    A --> B["orderBy
    (_, ['age','score'],
            ['asc','desc'])"]
    B --> C["1st: age ↑"]
    C --> D["2nd: score ↓"]
    D --> E["Sorted result"]\`}
  mobile={\`flowchart TB
    A["[{age:25,score:85},
      {age:25,score:80},
      {age:30,score:90}]"]
    A --> B["orderBy
    (_, ['age','score'],
            ['asc','desc'])"]
    B --> C["1st: age ↑"]
    C --> D["2nd: score ↓"]
    D --> E["Sorted result"]\`}
/>

### Multi-criteria logic
<ResponsiveMermaid
  desktop={\`flowchart LR
    S1["Compare age (asc)"]
    S1 -->|"25 = 25"| S2["Compare score (desc)"]
    S2 -->|"85 > 80"| R1["85 before 80"]\`}
  mobile={\`flowchart TB
    S1["Compare age (asc)"]
    S1 -->|"25 = 25"| S2["Compare score (desc)"]
    S2 -->|"85 > 80"| R1["85 before 80"]\`}
/>

---

## Use Cases

### Sort by multiple criteria 📌

Organize data with primary and secondary sort keys.
Perfect for data tables, leaderboards, or search results.

